----------------------------------------------------
/etc/group → stores group details
renuka@Bunny:~$ grep '^renuka:' /etc/group
renuka:x:1000:
-----------------------------------------
/etc/shadow → stores encrypted passwords
renuka@Bunny:~$ grep '^renuka:' /etc/shadow
grep: /etc/shadow: Permission denied
Why you got “Permission denied”

/etc/shadow is a highly protected system file because it stores all users’ encrypted passwords.

Only the root user (administrator) can read it.(use sudo)
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo grep '^renuka:' /etc/shadow
[sudo] password for renuka:
renuka:$y$j9T$1isHt5JsglKi6SModEQ9t0$9naDK/zjS5fj36GU7DrpbjJoEAbQshjmyPvJPJ6heb4:20372:0:99999:7:::
-----------------------------------------------------------------

passwd >> Used to set, change, or manage passwords for users in Linux
Change your own password : passwd
shiv@Bunny:~$ passwd
Changing password for shiv.
Current password:
New password:
Retype new password:
passwd: password updated successfully

renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo passwd -l renuka >> to lock ypur account
[sudo] password for renuka:
passwd: password changed.
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo passwd -S renuka >> to check the status weather its locked( L: LOCKED P: active)
renuka L 2025-10-11 0 99999 7 -1
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo passwd -u renuka >> to unlock your account
passwd: password changed.
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo passwd -S renuka
renuka P 2025-10-11 0 99999 7 -1
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
usermod >> Used to modify an existing user’s account — like changing username, home directory, shell, groups, etc.
Step 1 — Add a comment (user description)
O/P: renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo usermod -c "Test user for practice" shiv
renuka@Bunny:~$
renuka@Bunny:~$ grep '^shiv:' /etc/passwd
shiv:x:1001:1001:Test user for practice:/home/shiv:/bin/bash
Command: usermod -aG >> very common in real-world setups (especially to give sudo access).
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo usermod -aG sudo shiv
renuka@Bunny:~$
renuka@Bunny:~$ groups shiv
shiv : shiv sudo (now shiva has sudo access)
>> Command: usermod -l (rename user)
-------------------------------------------------------------
userdel >> Command: userdel
Used to delete a user account from the Linux system.

userdel username	Deletes the user but keeps the home directory.
userdel -r username	Deletes the user and their home directory & mail.
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo userdel -r sunny
userdel: user 'sunny' does not exist
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo rm -r /home/sunny
renuka@Bunny:~$ ls /home
harsha  renuka  shiv
----------------------------------------------
groupadd >> Create a new group
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo groupadd devteam
renuka@Bunny:~$ grep '^devteam:' /etc/group
devteam:x:1002:
--------------------------------------------
groupdel >> to delete a group 
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo groupdel devteam
-----------------------------------------------------------------
gpasswd >> t’s used to manage group membership and passwords for groups.
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo groupadd tester     ////////.. added group
renuka@Bunny:~$ grep '^tester:' /etc/group
tester:x:1002:
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo gpasswd -a shiv tester  >> here added user to that group(-a command)
Adding user shiv to group tester
renuka@Bunny:~$ grep '^tester:' /etc/group
tester:x:1002:shiv
>> how to remove (use -d)
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo gpasswd -d shiv tester
Removing user shiv from group tester
renuka@Bunny:~$ grep '^tester:' /etc/group
tester:x:1002:
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
su / sudo
su — Switch User
su - username
sudo → Run one command as an admin.( lets a normal user run commands with root (admin) privileges)

su → Switch to another user (like root).
example for sudo:
renuka@Bunny:~$ mkdir /test
mkdir: cannot create directory ‘/test’: Permission denied (Because only root (admin) can modify /.) so we used sudo
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo mkdir /test
renuka@Bunny:~$ ls -ld/test (( if you want to check at root level use this )) the reason you didn’t see /testfolder in your ls output is because you ran ls inside your home directory (~).
ls: invalid option -- '/'
Try 'ls --help' for more information.
renuka@Bunny:~$ ls -ld /test
drwxr-xr-x 1 root root 4096 Nov  1 09:50 /test

chown / chgrp:

renuka@Bunny:~$ ls -l
total 8
-rw-r--r-- 1 renuka renuka  173 Oct 25 10:59 compress.zip
-rw-r--r-- 1 renuka renuka 1024 Oct 25 10:58 f1.txt
-rw-r--r-- 1 renuka renuka 2048 Oct 25 10:58 f2.txt
drwxr-xr-x 1 renuka renuka 4096 Oct 25 10:46 folder1
renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo chown shiv f1.txt
[sudo] password for renuka:
renuka@Bunny:~$ ls -l
total 8
-rw-r--r-- 1 renuka renuka  173 Oct 25 10:59 compress.zip
-rw-r--r-- 1 shiv   renuka 1024 Oct 25 10:58 f1.txt
-rw-r--r-- 1 renuka renuka 2048 Oct 25 10:58 f2.txt
drwxr-xr-x 1 renuka renuka 4096 Oct 25 10:46 folder1
Change both owner and group

renuka@Bunny:~$ sudo chown shiv:tester f1.txt
renuka@Bunny:~$ ls -l
total 8
-rw-r--r-- 1 renuka renuka  173 Oct 25 10:59 compress.zip
-rw-r--r-- 1 shiv   tester 1024 Oct 25 10:58 f1.txt
-rw-r--r-- 1 renuka renuka 2048 Oct 25 10:58 f2.txt
drwxr-xr-x 1 renuka renuka 4096 Oct 25 10:46 folder1
renuka@Bunny:~$
chown → change owner or both (owner:group)

chgrp → change group only
